WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.180 --> 00:00:01.480
&gt;&gt; Maria Russo: Hello.

00:00:01.480 --> 00:00:03.180
Welcome.

00:00:03.180 --> 00:00:04.480
&gt;&gt; Hi Maria.

00:00:04.480 --> 00:00:05.780
&gt;&gt; Maria Russo: Hi.

00:00:05.780 --> 00:00:07.080
Welcome, everyone.

00:00:07.080 --> 00:00:08.680
I am Maria Russo.

00:00:08.680 --> 00:00:10.490
I am the Children's Books editor

00:00:10.490 --> 00:00:12.380
at the New York Times
Book Review.

00:00:12.380 --> 00:00:17.630
Yes, I know, I have the
best job in the world.

00:00:17.630 --> 00:00:20.760
[applause] It's especially
exciting when I get to meet some

00:00:20.760 --> 00:00:23.390
of the authors who
make such a difference

00:00:23.390 --> 00:00:26.000
in our children's
lives, with their books.

00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:30.130
And the author we have
today is especially amazing.

00:00:30.130 --> 00:00:33.450
I think she's someone
parents, and children,

00:00:33.450 --> 00:00:34.880
will be excited to see.

00:00:34.880 --> 00:00:40.420
The parents, of course,
because Danica McKellar is also

00:00:40.420 --> 00:00:42.520
an actress.

00:00:42.520 --> 00:00:47.930
Made a big difference in many of
our lives on "The Wonder Years".

00:00:47.930 --> 00:00:51.400
Later on, "The West Wing",
on the Hallmark Channel;

00:00:51.400 --> 00:00:53.790
we all have lots
of memories of her.

00:00:53.790 --> 00:00:55.800
But, I'm going to go
out on a limb and say,

00:00:55.800 --> 00:00:58.580
more important is
the work she's done

00:00:58.580 --> 00:01:02.730
to help children feel
comfortable with math.

00:01:02.730 --> 00:01:04.930
And love math the way she does.

00:01:04.930 --> 00:01:09.000
Because of course, in addition

00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:11.190
to all her other
accomplishments,

00:01:11.190 --> 00:01:17.450
she has a degree from UCLA
in math, she is a co-author

00:01:17.450 --> 00:01:20.420
of a theorem in math;

00:01:20.420 --> 00:01:23.540
she's really an overall
amazing person.

00:01:23.540 --> 00:01:27.280
So, let me just not
waste any more time.

00:01:27.280 --> 00:01:30.360
I just want to tell you
about her math book program

00:01:30.360 --> 00:01:32.580
for parents, if you're
not aware.

00:01:32.580 --> 00:01:38.050
Her books cover birth to high
school geometry at this point.

00:01:38.050 --> 00:01:40.310
The program is called
McKellar Math.

00:01:40.310 --> 00:01:43.620
You can go on her
website, mckellarmath.com

00:01:43.620 --> 00:01:46.350
and really see all the
books that she's done.

00:01:46.350 --> 00:01:49.890
Includes really, baby
books, books you can read

00:01:49.890 --> 00:01:54.820
to your newborn, "Bath time,
math time" is the most recent,

00:01:54.820 --> 00:01:57.830
bringing numbers into bath time.

00:01:57.830 --> 00:02:02.430
Another very recent
book is for ages 6 to 8,

00:02:02.430 --> 00:02:04.540
it's called "Do Not
Open This Math Book".

00:02:04.540 --> 00:02:09.410
So kids, do not open that book
if your parents bring it home.

00:02:09.410 --> 00:02:11.020
There it-- [laughter].

00:02:11.020 --> 00:02:14.220
And many, many more for the--

00:02:14.220 --> 00:02:16.390
I won't tell you the
titles of the teenage books

00:02:16.390 --> 00:02:18.890
because they're very
appealing to teenagers.

00:02:18.890 --> 00:02:20.840
We have a young crowd here.

00:02:20.840 --> 00:02:27.020
And so, I am so happy to welcome
a really important person

00:02:27.020 --> 00:02:29.290
in the world of children's
books, in the world

00:02:29.290 --> 00:02:32.800
of math, Danica McKellar.

00:02:39.510 --> 00:02:44.080
[ Applause ]

00:02:44.080 --> 00:02:45.380
&gt;&gt; Danica McKellar:
Hello, everyone.

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:46.680
How are you?

00:02:46.680 --> 00:02:47.980
[audience responding]
Oh, this is wonderful.

00:02:47.980 --> 00:02:50.760
I didn't know I was
going to have this.

00:02:50.760 --> 00:02:52.060
[laughter] That's great.

00:02:52.060 --> 00:02:53.360
I'm so glad to be here.

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:56.550
This is my first time at
this particular festival.

00:02:56.550 --> 00:02:59.690
It's not my first time in
Washington, D.C. though.

00:02:59.690 --> 00:03:03.290
The first, actually I would
say the last time I was

00:03:03.290 --> 00:03:05.900
in Washington, D.C.
speaking to a crowd,

00:03:05.900 --> 00:03:09.560
it was not at this festival,
but it was in the year 2000,

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:12.190
in front of a sub-committee
of Congress.

00:03:12.190 --> 00:03:15.290
And in some ways, that visit

00:03:15.290 --> 00:03:17.230
to Congress was the
beginning of McKellar Math.

00:03:17.230 --> 00:03:21.110
I'll tell you about
that in a minute.

00:03:21.110 --> 00:03:22.480
First, I want to back up.

00:03:22.480 --> 00:03:25.630
How many of you guys
remember "The Wonder Years"?

00:03:25.630 --> 00:03:26.930
[applause] Wow!

00:03:26.930 --> 00:03:28.230
That's great.

00:03:28.230 --> 00:03:30.620
I forget, I actually don't
need this microphone.

00:03:30.620 --> 00:03:32.130
It's psychological; see?

00:03:32.130 --> 00:03:37.500
Look, I can go like this and
you can hear me just as well.

00:03:37.500 --> 00:03:40.350
[laughter] So, how many of
you guys are afraid of math

00:03:40.350 --> 00:03:43.750
or had ever been afraid of math?

00:03:43.750 --> 00:03:47.900
Hey, this is actually a crowd
that's not too math-phobic.

00:03:47.900 --> 00:03:49.360
That's amazing.

00:03:49.360 --> 00:03:52.750
I was afraid of math,
during the time when I was

00:03:52.750 --> 00:03:54.050
on "The Wonder Years".

00:03:54.050 --> 00:03:57.720
When I was in the 7th grade,
that's when the show started.

00:03:57.720 --> 00:04:00.580
And I still remember, and my
mom is here in the audience,

00:04:00.580 --> 00:04:03.570
she still remembers me
coming home and crying

00:04:03.570 --> 00:04:06.080
because I was afraid
of my math homework.

00:04:06.080 --> 00:04:09.100
I'm sure most of us-- okay, I'm
actually thinking that a lot

00:04:09.100 --> 00:04:11.880
of you guys didn't admit
to being afraid of math,

00:04:11.880 --> 00:04:13.690
at some point in your life.

00:04:13.690 --> 00:04:15.990
How-- okay, I'll rephrase it.

00:04:15.990 --> 00:04:19.860
How many people remember
ever taking a math test

00:04:19.860 --> 00:04:21.980
and having fear?

00:04:21.980 --> 00:04:25.060
Like, that prickly feeling
in the back of your neck?

00:04:25.060 --> 00:04:26.820
Yes, okay; that's more like it.

00:04:26.820 --> 00:04:29.360
Thank you for being honest.

00:04:29.360 --> 00:04:32.740
So, when I was in the 7th grade,
I had a really interesting time

00:04:32.740 --> 00:04:36.850
because my teacher did not
explain the concepts very well.

00:04:36.850 --> 00:04:38.390
It was before I really
understood

00:04:38.390 --> 00:04:42.860
that math is a language and
it needs to be translated,

00:04:42.860 --> 00:04:45.570
otherwise it remains
foreign and scary.

00:04:45.570 --> 00:04:49.150
Now, midway through the 7th
grade, through this year

00:04:49.150 --> 00:04:52.980
of terror for me, our
teacher got switched out.

00:04:52.980 --> 00:04:54.360
We got a new teacher.

00:04:54.360 --> 00:04:55.660
And guess what happened?

00:04:55.660 --> 00:04:59.440
Do you think math got a
lot easier all of a sudden?

00:04:59.440 --> 00:05:02.820
Yes! The same exact
topics that had totally,

00:05:02.820 --> 00:05:05.270
totally scared me
suddenly made more sense.

00:05:05.270 --> 00:05:07.220
Like, so much more sense.

00:05:07.220 --> 00:05:10.440
And I'll never forget
this one quiz that I took.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:12.170
And it was that, we had
just gotten the new teacher

00:05:12.170 --> 00:05:14.450
so I hadn't really
gotten her influence yet.

00:05:14.450 --> 00:05:16.980
And like I was just saying
with you guys, you remember

00:05:16.980 --> 00:05:21.090
that feeling of being terrified
and just like, nauseous;

00:05:21.090 --> 00:05:22.780
you're sitting there in front
of the test and you're like,

00:05:22.780 --> 00:05:24.600
"I don't know what's
going to happen."

00:05:24.600 --> 00:05:27.240
That feeling of being
totally out of control.

00:05:27.240 --> 00:05:31.190
And it looked like
Chinese to me.

00:05:31.190 --> 00:05:33.240
And I had studied so hard.

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:36.380
And the bell rang, and
it was still blank.

00:05:36.380 --> 00:05:39.720
And I couldn't understand; I
mean, I was like trying not

00:05:39.720 --> 00:05:42.540
to cry and this new
teacher, Mrs. Jacobson,

00:05:42.540 --> 00:05:45.900
all the people were like getting
up and turning in their quizzes

00:05:45.900 --> 00:05:47.620
and leaving and I couldn't move.

00:05:47.620 --> 00:05:50.810
I was just terrified and
horrified and embarrassed

00:05:50.810 --> 00:05:55.540
and she let me stay,
for the entire recess

00:05:55.540 --> 00:05:59.140
and just her having that
kind of faith in me,

00:05:59.140 --> 00:06:01.770
I started like writing
some stuff down.

00:06:01.770 --> 00:06:04.980
Like, I started like at least
getting some stuff on the page.

00:06:04.980 --> 00:06:07.170
And I ended up getting
a C on that quiz,

00:06:07.170 --> 00:06:09.430
which was some sort of miracle.

00:06:09.430 --> 00:06:13.310
But that was like a huge turning
point for me, where I realized

00:06:13.310 --> 00:06:16.940
that my perception of my
experience and my perception

00:06:16.940 --> 00:06:19.890
of the math and the way
math was being presented,

00:06:19.890 --> 00:06:22.730
was so much a part
of the equation;

00:06:22.730 --> 00:06:25.390
not to like make a math pun.

00:06:25.390 --> 00:06:26.690
[laughter] But anyway,
that taught me

00:06:26.690 --> 00:06:28.930
that the way you
present math was huge.

00:06:28.930 --> 00:06:31.210
So, that was a huge
turning point for me.

00:06:31.210 --> 00:06:36.270
I ended up loving the challenge
of math and going to UCLA

00:06:36.270 --> 00:06:38.690
and getting a degree
in mathematics.

00:06:38.690 --> 00:06:41.460
Now, before I got my degree,
"The Wonder Years" ended right

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:42.760
at the end of high school.

00:06:42.760 --> 00:06:45.120
So, have you guys heard
about child stars?

00:06:45.120 --> 00:06:48.180
And some of the stuff that
happens to child stars?

00:06:48.180 --> 00:06:49.860
Sometimes?

00:06:49.860 --> 00:06:52.940
And right, yeah, they
end up; I mean, it's sad.

00:06:52.940 --> 00:06:54.350
And it's not across
the board, by the way;

00:06:54.350 --> 00:06:56.360
those are just the
stories that make the news.

00:06:56.360 --> 00:06:59.000
But sometimes, you know,
people fall on hard times

00:06:59.000 --> 00:07:00.660
and I'll tell you why.

00:07:00.660 --> 00:07:02.850
It's a self-esteem issue.

00:07:02.850 --> 00:07:05.230
So, when you're done
with your big show,

00:07:05.230 --> 00:07:08.080
you start to wonder
what your value would be

00:07:08.080 --> 00:07:11.170
if you didn't have that show,
because everywhere you go,

00:07:11.170 --> 00:07:12.560
that's what people talk about.

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:18.120
Imagine if, when you were like
I don't know, 12 years old,

00:07:18.120 --> 00:07:21.500
you were on the soccer team and
you scored this amazing goal.

00:07:21.500 --> 00:07:23.940
And everybody talked about it
and it was the winning goal

00:07:23.940 --> 00:07:25.240
and everybody was like, "Yay!

00:07:25.240 --> 00:07:26.600
That soccer goal!

00:07:26.600 --> 00:07:27.900
That was amazing.

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:29.200
You scored!

00:07:29.200 --> 00:07:30.500
You made the team win!"

00:07:30.500 --> 00:07:32.160
And then the next year, people
are still talking about it

00:07:32.160 --> 00:07:33.460
and it's like, "Okay,
that's cool."

00:07:33.460 --> 00:07:35.850
And then like, five years later,
they're still talking about it.

00:07:35.850 --> 00:07:38.410
And 10 years later, they're
like, "Aren't you the one

00:07:38.410 --> 00:07:39.980
who like scored that
soccer goal?"

00:07:39.980 --> 00:07:41.870
You're like, "Yes.

00:07:41.870 --> 00:07:43.360
That was me.

00:07:43.360 --> 00:07:45.180
But I do other things now too."

00:07:45.180 --> 00:07:51.260
Anyway, for me, mathematics
gave me this sense of self.

00:07:51.260 --> 00:07:53.110
Because it was hard, right?

00:07:53.110 --> 00:07:55.250
Math can be challenging;
it can be really hard.

00:07:55.250 --> 00:07:58.530
But when you stick it through
and you just like keep trying,

00:07:58.530 --> 00:08:00.660
it gives you this
sort of confidence

00:08:00.660 --> 00:08:02.830
that comes from feeling smart.

00:08:02.830 --> 00:08:04.340
And I got addicted to that.

00:08:04.340 --> 00:08:07.110
And it really helped
me get through those,

00:08:07.110 --> 00:08:10.940
like "post-child star years"
at UCLA, where everybody,

00:08:10.940 --> 00:08:12.250
every day, said, "Hey, Winnie.

00:08:12.250 --> 00:08:13.620
Where's Kevin?"

00:08:13.620 --> 00:08:17.770
You know? It's like,
"He's not here.

00:08:17.770 --> 00:08:19.070
And my name isn't 'Winnie'".

00:08:19.070 --> 00:08:23.910
So, but let's face it, you don't
have to have been a child star

00:08:23.910 --> 00:08:26.360
to struggle with your
self-esteem and your sense

00:08:26.360 --> 00:08:27.900
of self as a teen girl.

00:08:27.900 --> 00:08:30.270
And that is also part of
what inspired the books.

00:08:30.270 --> 00:08:32.060
So let's fast forward now.

00:08:32.060 --> 00:08:36.790
I've gotten my degree in
mathematics and it became,

00:08:36.790 --> 00:08:40.200
it became well known that I
had gotten this degree in math.

00:08:40.200 --> 00:08:42.090
People would-- it
like made headlines,

00:08:42.090 --> 00:08:44.630
"Winnie is a math whiz".

00:08:44.630 --> 00:08:48.460
But the cool thing that came
from that is that I was invited

00:08:48.460 --> 00:08:50.870
to speak in front of a
sub-committee of Congress

00:08:50.870 --> 00:08:53.600
about the importance of
women in mathematics.

00:08:53.600 --> 00:08:56.760
There-- how many of you guys
live here and work in politics

00:08:56.760 --> 00:08:58.960
in any way, shape
or form whatsoever?

00:08:58.960 --> 00:09:00.370
Just curious.

00:09:00.370 --> 00:09:01.670
A little bit, okay.

00:09:01.670 --> 00:09:04.480
So there was a committee
who wanted to raise money,

00:09:04.480 --> 00:09:07.900
who wanted money from the
government for scholarships

00:09:07.900 --> 00:09:10.450
for women in math, in college.

00:09:10.450 --> 00:09:13.870
And, they invited me to
come speak and testify

00:09:13.870 --> 00:09:16.040
about the importance of women in
math, because I was sort of the

00:09:16.040 --> 00:09:19.170
"celebrity math person",
math girl.

00:09:19.170 --> 00:09:24.350
And I read their 100-page
report, that they sent me.

00:09:24.350 --> 00:09:28.900
I read every detail and it
was clear, in their report,

00:09:28.900 --> 00:09:30.200
and this was a lot of reading.

00:09:30.200 --> 00:09:31.500
It was pretty dense.

00:09:31.500 --> 00:09:33.390
I did research; I like, I
took this very seriously.

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:36.060
I mean, I was like going to
"serve my country" or something.

00:09:36.060 --> 00:09:37.780
And, that's how I
thought of it anyway.

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:39.800
I didn't think of it as a
commission that was using me

00:09:39.800 --> 00:09:41.100
to try to get more money.

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:42.450
I didn't think of
it like that at all.

00:09:42.450 --> 00:09:44.080
In fact, just the opposite.

00:09:44.080 --> 00:09:47.080
So, I read this report
and it was clear to me,

00:09:47.080 --> 00:09:49.810
that college is too late.

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.110
It's too late by then.

00:09:51.110 --> 00:09:52.610
I was a girl in college,

00:09:52.610 --> 00:09:56.520
and I was a professional
mathematician for a summer.

00:09:56.520 --> 00:09:58.950
I helped to prove a new
theorem and I got a stipend

00:09:58.950 --> 00:10:00.710
for that; I got money for that.

00:10:00.710 --> 00:10:03.610
And it wasn't hard,
because I was female.

00:10:03.610 --> 00:10:06.390
It would have been
easier if I'd have been

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:07.920
from a ethnic minority
group as well.

00:10:07.920 --> 00:10:11.560
So, I'm like, "You guys, this
is not where we need the money."

00:10:11.560 --> 00:10:14.980
And I'm telling this to
Congress, not realizing

00:10:14.980 --> 00:10:17.250
that the commission wanted
me to help them get money.

00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:19.500
Anyway, I said, "You
guys, it's in the report!"

00:10:19.500 --> 00:10:22.820
I read the 100 pages and
my dad famously loves

00:10:22.820 --> 00:10:25.970
to tell me the story that "You
looked at Congress and you said,

00:10:25.970 --> 00:10:28.160
'You probably didn't have a
chance to read all 100 pages,

00:10:28.160 --> 00:10:29.460
but I did.'" [laughter] Yes.

00:10:29.460 --> 00:10:33.440
And I said, "And it wasn't
in the executive summary."

00:10:33.440 --> 00:10:36.030
And it's true, it wasn't
in their executive summary.

00:10:36.030 --> 00:10:38.650
Middle school is the
time when girls start

00:10:38.650 --> 00:10:40.170
to lose competence in math.

00:10:40.170 --> 00:10:41.930
That's when it drops
off, it's middle school.

00:10:41.930 --> 00:10:43.230
It's too late by college.

00:10:43.230 --> 00:10:46.080
By college, they've
already dropped out of math.

00:10:46.080 --> 00:10:48.990
So I was-- and I really took
this seriously, and I mean,

00:10:48.990 --> 00:10:51.990
I took an oath and I was going
to tell the truth and I--

00:10:51.990 --> 00:10:55.090
didn't occur to me that I
was going against the people

00:10:55.090 --> 00:10:56.390
who had brought me out there.

00:10:56.390 --> 00:10:57.690
That's okay.

00:10:57.690 --> 00:10:58.990
And they didn't get the money.

00:10:58.990 --> 00:11:01.160
[laughter] But I told, I
said, I said, "I," I said,

00:11:01.160 --> 00:11:03.080
"math needs better P.R.

00:11:03.080 --> 00:11:04.380
; we need to help these girls.

00:11:04.380 --> 00:11:07.140
We also need stronger middle
school teachers because so many

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:08.960
of them are thrown
into a situation

00:11:08.960 --> 00:11:10.260
that they're not ready for.

00:11:10.260 --> 00:11:12.000
You know, they're the
gym teacher or the such

00:11:12.000 --> 00:11:14.160
and such teacher and because
we don't have enough money

00:11:14.160 --> 00:11:15.550
for middle school math teachers,

00:11:15.550 --> 00:11:17.700
we're not attracting
enough good talent.

00:11:17.700 --> 00:11:21.540
So this is where we need
to put our emphasis."

00:11:21.540 --> 00:11:25.680
And I pledged to Congress that
day, "I will do everything I can

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:27.050
to get math better P.R."

00:11:27.050 --> 00:11:30.020
I said, "I feel like I'm in
a unique position to do so.

00:11:30.020 --> 00:11:31.320
And this is what
I pledge to you."

00:11:31.320 --> 00:11:33.530
So yes, right here
in Washington, D.C.,

00:11:33.530 --> 00:11:36.020
this is the beginning, this was
the genesis of McKellar Math,

00:11:36.020 --> 00:11:40.220
when I made that pledge
to Congress back in 2000.

00:11:40.220 --> 00:11:41.560
So, [applause] aw, thank you.

00:11:41.560 --> 00:11:44.300
It was right here, in this city.

00:11:44.300 --> 00:11:48.440
And then a few years later,
I wrote my first book.

00:11:48.440 --> 00:11:50.980
It was called, and
I think it's okay

00:11:50.980 --> 00:11:53.580
to say this; can
I say this title?

00:11:53.580 --> 00:11:57.800
I can say the title of my
book: "Math Doesn't Suck".

00:11:57.800 --> 00:11:59.490
Maria didn't want to
say it in my intro.

00:11:59.490 --> 00:12:02.530
Look, I'm appealing to
middle school kids, okay?

00:12:02.530 --> 00:12:06.470
Yeah, "Math Doesn't Suck: How
to Survive Middle School Math

00:12:06.470 --> 00:12:09.620
Without Losing Your Mind
or Breaking a Nail."

00:12:09.620 --> 00:12:12.110
And the whole point was, "Look.

00:12:12.110 --> 00:12:13.410
Math is not just for boys.

00:12:13.410 --> 00:12:15.380
Math can be for everyone.

00:12:15.380 --> 00:12:20.480
You can be smart and savvy and
yes, a fabulous, glamorous girl,

00:12:20.480 --> 00:12:22.020
if that's what you want.

00:12:22.020 --> 00:12:24.350
You don't have to
choose one or the other".

00:12:24.350 --> 00:12:27.030
So that became my
platform for a while.

00:12:27.030 --> 00:12:30.120
It was my pledge to Congress,
"This is what I'm going to do;

00:12:30.120 --> 00:12:32.600
give math better P.R. and I'm
going to focus mostly on girls"

00:12:32.600 --> 00:12:34.080
and I did that for my
middle school books.

00:12:34.080 --> 00:12:37.030
So that's "Math Doesn't Suck,"
which teaches fractions,

00:12:37.030 --> 00:12:39.040
decimals, percents,
things like that.

00:12:39.040 --> 00:12:41.560
"Kiss My Math" which
is pre-algebra.

00:12:41.560 --> 00:12:46.000
And there's [laughter] I feel
bad, "Hot X: Algebra Exposed";

00:12:46.000 --> 00:12:47.970
that is the algebra book.

00:12:47.970 --> 00:12:53.560
And then "Girls Get Curves:
Geometry Takes Shape"

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:55.730
for high school geometry.

00:12:55.730 --> 00:12:57.280
So those are those books,

00:12:57.280 --> 00:12:59.370
and they were New York
Times best sellers,

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:01.240
they still sell really well.

00:13:01.240 --> 00:13:04.800
I'm super proud of them and
they are both math books

00:13:04.800 --> 00:13:09.290
that teach math, using really
fun analogies and also,

00:13:09.290 --> 00:13:11.010
self-esteem building books.

00:13:11.010 --> 00:13:14.320
They're books where I say,
"Look, you can do this.

00:13:14.320 --> 00:13:17.410
You know, a diamond is
formed under pressure.

00:13:17.410 --> 00:13:21.280
You know, when math gets hard,
when you think you can't do it

00:13:21.280 --> 00:13:24.200
and you struggle with it and
you stick with it anyway,

00:13:24.200 --> 00:13:26.590
and then you finally solve it,

00:13:26.590 --> 00:13:29.420
this is what I call
a math high."

00:13:29.420 --> 00:13:32.020
It's, you teach yourself
that you're stronger

00:13:32.020 --> 00:13:33.940
and smarter than you thought.

00:13:33.940 --> 00:13:36.530
And that is a gift that
you'll give yourself

00:13:36.530 --> 00:13:39.180
that nobody can give
you except for you,

00:13:39.180 --> 00:13:41.520
and nobody can take away.

00:13:41.520 --> 00:13:43.320
[applause] Thank you.

00:13:43.320 --> 00:13:47.040
[ Applause ]

00:13:47.040 --> 00:13:49.110
Building that kind
of self-confidence,

00:13:49.110 --> 00:13:51.270
that comes from feeling
smart, that doesn't come

00:13:51.270 --> 00:13:52.720
from the outside
world, that doesn't come

00:13:52.720 --> 00:13:54.370
from the clothes you're
wearing or the makeup

00:13:54.370 --> 00:13:56.340
or how many selfies you take
or how many likes you have

00:13:56.340 --> 00:14:00.970
on Instagram; all that stuff
is fun and it's superficial;

00:14:00.970 --> 00:14:04.980
it's not going to give you that
feeling inside that you need

00:14:04.980 --> 00:14:06.320
to survive in this world.

00:14:06.320 --> 00:14:10.340
Because life, is
challenging in so many ways.

00:14:10.340 --> 00:14:12.820
In so many ways that you
don't see on social media.

00:14:12.820 --> 00:14:15.990
So many-- the everyday
stuff is tough, right?

00:14:15.990 --> 00:14:18.540
When you're a kid, I see a
lot of kids in the middle,

00:14:18.540 --> 00:14:20.470
in the front here, on
these lovely bean bags.

00:14:20.470 --> 00:14:22.630
Why don't I have a bean bag?

00:14:22.630 --> 00:14:23.970
I want a bean bag.

00:14:23.970 --> 00:14:27.330
You have to be in math
class anyway, right?

00:14:27.330 --> 00:14:29.320
You have to be in math class.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:33.510
Okay. So math happens
to be a great place

00:14:33.510 --> 00:14:35.430
to sharpen your brain.

00:14:35.430 --> 00:14:36.730
It's just a great opportunity.

00:14:36.730 --> 00:14:38.030
And since you have
to be there anyway,

00:14:38.030 --> 00:14:41.540
why not use that opportunity
to sharpen your brain for real

00:14:41.540 --> 00:14:43.330
and get stronger and smarter,

00:14:43.330 --> 00:14:45.970
because those tools will help
you no matter what you do

00:14:45.970 --> 00:14:47.270
in your life.

00:14:47.270 --> 00:14:52.220
For real. Listen to what I say.

00:14:52.220 --> 00:14:54.160
[laughter] So, those
are the books for girls.

00:14:54.160 --> 00:14:57.720
Then I had parents, "Can
we write books for boys?

00:14:57.720 --> 00:14:59.020
Can you go younger?"

00:14:59.020 --> 00:15:00.470
And I'm thinking, "Okay,
yeah maybe younger."

00:15:00.470 --> 00:15:04.330
At the time, so I had my son,
he was one years old and I said,

00:15:04.330 --> 00:15:06.410
"You guys, I'm taking a break
from writing, because I want

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:09.950
to spend time with my
little guy" and I did.

00:15:09.950 --> 00:15:11.670
And then a few years later,

00:15:11.670 --> 00:15:13.200
once he became a
little more independent,

00:15:13.200 --> 00:15:17.220
I started writing again and I
answered the call of the parents

00:15:17.220 --> 00:15:19.060
which is, "Okay, we'll
do some co-ed books

00:15:19.060 --> 00:15:20.930
and we'll go younger".

00:15:20.930 --> 00:15:25.240
What I didn't realize was that
math was about to change and,

00:15:25.240 --> 00:15:27.630
for these like little kids.

00:15:27.630 --> 00:15:32.070
Okay, how many of you guys
are aware of common core math?

00:15:32.070 --> 00:15:35.340
Yes. How many of
you guys are like,

00:15:35.340 --> 00:15:37.370
"Why did they change math?"

00:15:37.370 --> 00:15:38.730
Yeah, why?

00:15:38.730 --> 00:15:41.180
It's not, like it's
not necessarily

00:15:41.180 --> 00:15:44.550
that it's bad, it's just "Why?"

00:15:44.550 --> 00:15:47.390
Well, I actually think
there are some good things

00:15:47.390 --> 00:15:49.400
about common core math, I do.

00:15:49.400 --> 00:15:50.770
There are some good things.

00:15:50.770 --> 00:15:54.480
But it does make the math
itself look more complicated.

00:15:54.480 --> 00:15:57.400
So parents are saying to me,
"I don't know how to help my 6

00:15:57.400 --> 00:15:59.780
and 7 year old with
their math homework.

00:15:59.780 --> 00:16:01.620
How did this happen?"

00:16:01.620 --> 00:16:03.850
You know, and I agree.

00:16:03.850 --> 00:16:08.490
As parents, you figure,
"Okay, I want to help my kid

00:16:08.490 --> 00:16:10.770
in any way I can, and someday
the math might get so hard

00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:12.070
that I won't be able to do it."

00:16:12.070 --> 00:16:13.720
Luckily, getting a degree
in math, I saved myself

00:16:13.720 --> 00:16:16.160
from that one, but it's
very common, right?

00:16:16.160 --> 00:16:17.460
Because math is the
kind of thing,

00:16:17.460 --> 00:16:19.970
if you don't practice
it, you'll forget it.

00:16:19.970 --> 00:16:24.340
So, how many of you guys have
kids that age, 6 and 7-ish,

00:16:24.340 --> 00:16:26.620
and you've already
run into that issue?

00:16:26.620 --> 00:16:28.180
Where like, "Why does
this look different?"

00:16:28.180 --> 00:16:30.950
Yeah. So, I couldn't
believe that there isn't--

00:16:30.950 --> 00:16:33.720
and common core started
I believe around 2011.

00:16:33.720 --> 00:16:36.490
And I think it was
implemented throughout states

00:16:36.490 --> 00:16:37.790
at different rates.

00:16:37.790 --> 00:16:40.680
But I had-- so I couldn't
believe there wasn't a resource

00:16:40.680 --> 00:16:45.650
that helps parents and kids
with the new way it's taught.

00:16:45.650 --> 00:16:47.940
So I did that.

00:16:47.940 --> 00:16:52.080
That's this book, "Do
Not Open This Math Book!"

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:53.900
This is for ages 6 to 8.

00:16:53.900 --> 00:16:56.250
It addresses the
addition and subtraction

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:57.560
and the new way they teach it.

00:16:57.560 --> 00:17:00.160
So, there's all sorts
of new vocabulary.

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:01.670
In fact, at the end of the book,

00:17:01.670 --> 00:17:06.570
I have the "new math"
translation guide for grownups.

00:17:06.570 --> 00:17:09.710
[applause] Because they
don't call it "borrowing"

00:17:09.710 --> 00:17:11.010
and "carrying" anymore.

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:13.290
Because you're not
technically borrowing it

00:17:13.290 --> 00:17:15.540
because you're not going to
give it back; okay, fine.

00:17:15.540 --> 00:17:17.560
But the carrying, I
actually think is not bad;

00:17:17.560 --> 00:17:19.320
I don't know why they
changed that one.

00:17:19.320 --> 00:17:23.030
But now it's regrouping and
ungrouping and some people call

00:17:23.030 --> 00:17:26.910
"ungrouping" and regrouping;
there's not even uniform.

00:17:26.910 --> 00:17:29.610
But anyway, I break it down
and I make it super fun.

00:17:29.610 --> 00:17:32.890
And like all my books, the
point is, "Let's make this fun.

00:17:32.890 --> 00:17:34.840
Let's make it accessible
and doable."

00:17:34.840 --> 00:17:36.380
And so there's all
sorts of cartoons

00:17:36.380 --> 00:17:37.750
and Mr. Mouse is the guy.

00:17:37.750 --> 00:17:39.900
Mr. Mouse is the one
who's afraid of math.

00:17:39.900 --> 00:17:42.790
He's the one saying,
"Don't open this book!"

00:17:42.790 --> 00:17:45.050
You got a copy; so
there are comics,

00:17:45.050 --> 00:17:48.100
there's also a little
cartoons where a parent

00:17:48.100 --> 00:17:49.900
and child can read it together.

00:17:49.900 --> 00:17:52.290
Draco, my son and I,
we like doing that.

00:17:52.290 --> 00:17:54.340
He likes reading the
Mr. Mouse character.

00:17:54.340 --> 00:17:57.080
Mr. Mouse is always
causing trouble.

00:17:57.080 --> 00:17:58.700
So why not teach
math in the context

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:01.550
that kids are going
to respond to?

00:18:01.550 --> 00:18:02.990
Right? Why not?

00:18:02.990 --> 00:18:06.630
We have choices and why
not make that choice.

00:18:06.630 --> 00:18:09.530
So that is, "Do Not
Open This Math Book".

